textMap.PRIMARY: Of Strange Lands and People, Op. 15, No. 1

Bonus Content: This episode of "The Man in the High Castle" is one of a number of titles that benefit from exclusive videos and behind-the-scenes photos, accessible in the X-Ray Bonus tab in Prime Video.

In Philip K. Dick's the novel a local paper claims that Joe and his wife, "Mrs. Cinnadella" got into a fight at the hotel, during which, she dispatched him. Juliana is never identified and she was not, in fact, married to Joe.
During the Second World War, Ahnenerbe, in collaboration with the Nazi Institute for Military Scientific Research, conducted several experiments on human test subjects.

The Many-Worlds Interpretation, which is suggested by Philip K. Dick's book and is central to the TV series, (also known as multiverse theory, the Everett interpretation, and the theory of universal wave function) proposes that multiple universes exist in parallel with the perceivable universe, and that all possible versions of the universe in the past and future have been achieved and will be achieved.

John Smith and Kido fought on opposite sides of the conflict in the Solomon Islands during the war in the Pacific. There is an underlying mutual respect between the two army veterans, despite the fact that they come from rival nations.

In "The Man in the High Castle," the Nazis pioneered satellite technology. Therefore, it would make sense that Himmler frequently communicates with the Reichsmarshall of America over satellite television link from Berlin.

Generally speaking, the Japanese enforce less rigid Neutral Zone border controls than the Nazis, largely because they are less concerned about undesirables who wish to leave the JPS and do not have the same kind of racial policies that require enforcement.
Series creatives wanted to instill the Grand Palace with a sense of potential danger at all the times. In this space, everyone is always watching everyone else.

There is some limited public infrastructure installed in the Neutral Zone, under contract by the Reich and Japanese authorities. This includes several maintained highways that cross the zone, including the old Route 66 and railways that link the JPS to the Reich.

Series creatives loved the Grand Palace location. The low ceilings, the way the light filtered into the space and the color palette gave it beautiful but mysterious visual impact that matches the noir-adjacent style of the series.
Many viewers will remember Lem as an old friend (and one-time foe) of Juliana's from Season 2 of "The Man in the High Castle."
Ed and Frank have been friends for 22 years. They grew up together in San Francisco and witnessed all the highs and lows of war and occupation side-by-side.
The leader of the American Reich is the Reichsmarshall of North America; this is the Nazi equivalent of being President of the United States.

There are no public elections in the Reich, which is a one-party state. All civil servants, members of the judiciary and government officials are selected by a ranking Nazi committee, a regional cabinet, the Berlin cabinet, or by the Führer.

In the alt history, the existence of a Torah anywhere on the North American continent is extremely uncommon and therefore extraordinary. The Nazis would surely have burned all copies the happened upon across the globe.
A Torah can only be written by hand by a trained Jewish scribe. In the American Reich, such individuals are rare. There may only be one amongst the group hiding at Sabra.
